<section class="card">
  <h2>Yukon Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Yukon gardening is defined by short frost-free windows, intense summer daylight,
    and rapid seasonal transitions. While the calendar season is brief, long daylight hours
    can drive impressive growth when crops are chosen realistically.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Long daylight is your advantage</h3>
  <p>
    Peak summer brings extended daylight that promotes strong vegetative growth.
    Leafy greens, brassicas, and root crops often thrive despite the limited overall season.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re selecting crops for a tight window,
    <a href="/guides/crops-that-mature-in-under-90-frost-free-days/">
      this list of crops that mature in under 90 frost-free days
    </a>
    can help narrow your options.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Frost frames the entire plan</h3>
  <p>
    Late spring frost risk can persist, and fall frost often arrives decisively.
    Warm-season crops must be started early and protected if you want a realistic chance of harvest.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    To understand how frost timing and heat accumulation interact,
    see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">
      how frost dates and growing degree days work together
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Soil warming may lag behind air temperature</h3>
  <p>
    Even when daytime highs look promising, soil temperatures can remain too cool for
    direct-seeded warm crops. Raised beds, dark mulches, and protected structures
    help accelerate warming.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Microclimates matter significantly</h3>
  <p>
    South-facing walls, windbreaks, and well-drained sites frequently outperform open ground.
    In northern climates, even modest shelter can compound into meaningful gains.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If your garden seems warmer or colder than nearby areas,
    <a href="/guides/how-microclimates-change-frost-dates/">
      this explains how microclimates shift frost timing
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Use frost dates to establish your planting boundaries.</li>
    <li>Favor very short-maturity and cold-tolerant crops.</li>
    <li>Plan protection if attempting heat-loving varieties.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Yukon, crop selection and smart protection are often more important than precise planting dates.
  </p>
</section>